content:
Salesforce is modifying internal implementations of our own Lightning components, Salesforce Lightning Design System (SLDS) styles, and custom properties to support future UI changes. These internal changes won’t cause visible UI changes for most customers.

If you customize your components or sites using supported techniques, we expect these changes to have little to no impact on your customizations. However, if your components use unsupported customizations, we recommend that you update them to use supported techniques to prevent visual regressions.

These changes apply to Lightning Experience, Experience Cloud sites, and all versions of the Salesforce mobile app in all editions. 

Starting in the Summer ’24 release, we’re changing the internals of some UI components, which can change the rendered DOM. Don’t modify the DOM elements of Salesforce components via CSS or JavaScript or target SLDS classes in unit tests.

Some visual regressions are possible if you customize Lightning pages or Experience Cloud sites by targeting Salesforce components and CSS styles that change with the architecture updates. Visual regressions can range from a UI component displaying a slightly different color to layout changes in your UI.

For information about supported and unsupported customization techniques, and how to update your customizations, see the SLDS Architecture Updates FAQ.
title: Confirming Custom Component Design System Compliance
